SIMPLE: political
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Political
<hw>Po*lit"i*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Having, or conforming to, a settled system of administration.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>political</xex> government.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to public policy, or to politics;
relating to affairs of state or administration; <as>as, a
<ex>political</ex> writer</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>political</xex>
state of Europe.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Paley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a party, or to parties, in the
state; <as>as, his <ex>political</ex> relations were with the
Whigs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Politic; wise; also, artful.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sterne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Political economy</b></col>, <cd>that branch of political
science or philosophy which treats of the sources, and methods of
production and preservation, of the material wealth and prosperity of
nations.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Politicalism</ent>⟦br⟧
